                "caption": "Figure 1:Intrinsic Sparsity in 1.58-bit BitNet.We present the aggregated weight statistics averaged across all linear layers of the pre-trained 1.58-bit BitNet (2B) model(Maet al.,2025b).\n(A) The distribution of normalized latent weights exhibits a distinct quantization-valley structure, where the majority of values fall within the [-0.5, 0.5] rounding interval.\n(B) Consequently,the quantized discrete states are dominated by zeros (approx. 42.3%), confirming that BitNet naturally converges to a highly sparse representation without explicit pruning.",
                "position": 250
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.05168/2603.05168v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Comparison of N:M sparsity friendliness between 1.58-bit BitNet and full-precision models.Normalized PPL increase relative to each method’s dense (8:8) counterpart.\nThe dashed line marks a 10% degradation threshold.\nAt 2:4 (50% sparsity; same ratio as 4:8), BF16 exceeds the threshold (+18.8%) while BitNet remains below it (+5.7%), indicating 1.58-bit BitNet is more sparsity-friendly than full-precision models.",
